{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638023"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:48:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:48:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17682"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17682"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.11,0.05,0.47,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10396"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78223"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10396"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17682"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63632"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10495"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24284"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24293"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78223","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78223"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBlood vessels in certain organs demonstrate an intrinsic ability to regulate blood flow independently of neural or hormonal control. This autoregulation is essential for maintaining constant perfusion despite changes in systemic blood pressure.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the myogenic mechanism of blood flow regulation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vasodilation in response to increased blood viscosity","Vasodilation in response to decreased oxygen tension","Vasoconstriction in response to increased metabolic activity","Vasoconstriction in response to increased transmural pressure","Vasoconstriction in response to decreased transmural pressure"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Evasoconstriction in response to increased transmural pressure\u003C/strong\u003E describes the myogenic mechanism. When blood pressure increases, the vessel wall stretches, triggering smooth muscle contraction. This reduces vessel diameter and helps maintain constant blood flow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVasodilation in response to increased blood viscosity\u003C/strong\u003E - Changes in blood viscosity do not directly trigger the myogenic response\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVasodilation in response to decreased oxygen tension\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes metabolic autoregulation rather than the myogenic mechanism\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVasoconstriction in response to increased metabolic activity\u003C/strong\u003E - Increased metabolic activity actually causes vasodilation to increase blood flow to tissues\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVasoconstriction in response to decreased transmural pressure\u003C/strong\u003E - The myogenic response works in the opposite way, with decreased pressure causing vasodilation\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe myogenic response is particularly important in organs requiring precise blood flow regulation, such as the kidneys, brain, and heart. It helps protect capillary beds from damage due to excessive pressure and maintains stable tissue perfusion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The myogenic mechanism in blood vessels refers to the intrinsic ability of vascular smooth muscle to contract in response to increased transmural pressure.","The myogenic response helps maintain constant blood flow despite changes in arterial pressure.","This mechanism is particularly important in the kidneys, brain, and heart where autoregulation of blood flow is critical."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63632"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17682"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63632"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T21:43:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T21:45:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10396"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78223"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (ident